Take for example, a simple C program to calculate the division of two numbers. In this case, we have to consider the scenario where the denominator is zero. To handle this, we can write:

if (denominator != 0) {
	result = numerator / denominator;
} else {
	printf('Error: Division by zero');
}

This way, we ensure that the program doesn't crash when the denominator is zero and gives a meaningful error message instead.

